[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] Each AWS Lambda instance runs within a lightweight, isolated environment powered by Firecracker microVMs.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] These microVMs are initialized with a runtime environment based on Amazon Linux (Amazon Linux AMI or Amazon Linux 2).
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] Firecracker provides hardware-virtualization-based isolation, aiming to achieve near-bare-metal performance with minimal overhead.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] AWS claims that, unlike traditional virtual machines, these microVMs launch in milliseconds, enabling rapid and secure function execution with a minimal memory footprint.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] The Amazon Linux AMI is specifically optimized for cloud-native and serverless workloads, aiming to provide a lightweight, secure, and performant runtime environment.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] As of 2025, AWS Lambda supports Node.js, Python, Java, Go, .NET, Ruby and custom runtimes.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] Rust and Go generally exhibit lower cold start times in AWS Lambda compared to Java and C# because they compile to native static binaries, eliminating the need for a virtual machine (JVM or .NET CLR) and reducing runtime initialization overhead.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] Go has some minimal runtime initialization, including garbage collection and goroutine management, but its impact on cold start time is relatively low.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] Rust, which is fully ahead-of-time (AOT) compiled and does not require a runtime, often achieves the lowest cold start latency among supported languages.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] Java and C# run on managed runtime environments, introducing additional cold start latency due to runtime initialization and Just-In-Time (JIT) compilation.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] However, modern optimizations have mitigated some of these challenges. .NET 7 and .NET 8 support Ahead-of-Time (AOT) compilation, reducing cold start times by precompiling code.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] Additionally, AWS Lambda SnapStart for Java 11 and 17 pre-warms and snapshots execution state, significantly decreasing cold start overhead for Java-based functions.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] Despite these optimizations, Rust and Go typically maintain lower cold start times due to their minimal runtime dependencies.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] In long-running workloads, JIT compilation in Java and .NET may improve execution speed through dynamic optimizations.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] However, this benefit is workload-dependent, and Rust's AOT compilation often provides better performance consistency, particularly for CPU-bound tasks.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] For short-lived Lambda invocations, Rust and Go generally maintain more predictable performance, as JIT optimizations may not have sufficient time to take effect.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] Historically, Rust and Go required additional effort in deployment due to cross-compilation and static linking challenges.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] Rust, in particular, often necessitates MUSL-based static linking for AWS Lambda compatibility.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] However, advancements in deployment tooling, including AWS Serverless Application Model (AWS SAM), GitHub Actions, and Lambda container images, have simplified this process.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] Go benefits from native static linking support, making its deployment process comparatively straightforward.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] AWS Lambda's support for container images further reduces runtime compatibility concerns, enabling the use of custom runtimes and dependencies.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] Reserved Concurrency sets a maximum number of concurrent executions for a specific function and reserves that capacity from the account's overall concurrency limit.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] However, it does not keep execution environments initialized or guarantee that any instances remain running when the function is idle.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] Provisioned Concurrency, in contrast, maintains a specified number of pre-initialized execution environments, ensuring that the function does not experience cold starts and does not scale down to zero.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] The Lambda Function URL gives Lambda a unique and permanent URL which can be accessed by authenticated and non-authenticated users alike.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] AWS Lambda layer is a ZIP archive containing libraries, frameworks or custom code that can be added to AWS Lambda functions.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] Migration from AWS Lambda to other AWS compute services, such as Amazon ECS, presents challenges due to tight integration with AWS Lambda's APIs, often referred to as service lock-in.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] Tools like AWS Lambda Web Adapter offer a pathway for portability by enabling developers to build web applications using familiar frameworks under a monolithic Lambda design pattern.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] However, this approach introduces limitations, including coarser-grained alerting and access controls, potential cold start delays with large dependencies, and limited suitability for non-HTTP APIs.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] AWS Lambda Powertools is an open-source library developed by AWS that provides utilities for AWS Lambda functions.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] The core utilities includes structured logging, metrics and tracing.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] It also offers other utilities for common use cases when developing AWS Lambda functions.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] As of March 2025, it also includes data masking support for Python.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] As of March 2025, AWS Lambda supports limited vertical scaling by increasing the number of virtual central processing units (vCPUs) through memory allocation.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] However, it does not allow an increase in single-thread performance, as clock speed remains fixed.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] When a function is allocated only one vCPU, multiple threads share the same core, resulting in context switching rather than true parallel execution.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] As a result, multi-threading in single-vCPU environments is primarily beneficial for input/output (I/O)-bound workloads rather than computationally intensive tasks.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] Allocating additional memory in AWS Lambda enables multiple vCPUs, allowing for parallel execution.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] However, the clock speed per core remains unchanged, limiting individual thread performance.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] This configuration makes AWS Lambda suitable for workloads that scale horizontally or leverage parallelism but less optimal for applications that require high single-thread performance.
[src:serverless-framework/aws-lambda] In April 2022, researchers found cryptomining malware targeting AWS Lambda named "Denonia".
[src:serverless-framework/function-as-a-service] Function as a Service is a subset of the serverless computing ecosystem.
[src:serverless-framework/function-as-a-service] The "Grain of Sand Anti-pattern" refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:serverless-framework/function-as-a-service] "Lambda Pinball" is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure Functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:serverless-framework/function-as-a-service] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:serverless-framework/function-as-a-service] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:serverless-framework/function-as-a-service] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:serverless-framework/function-as-a-service] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:serverless-framework/function-as-a-service] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:serverless-framework/function-as-a-service] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:serverless-framework/function-as-a-service] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:serverless-framework/function-as-a-service] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:serverless-framework/function-as-a-service] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:serverless-framework/function-as-a-service] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:serverless-framework/function-as-a-service] Function as a service workloads may encounter migration obstacles due to service lock-in from tight vendor integrations.
[src:serverless-framework/function-as-a-service] Hexagonal architecture can facilitate workload portability.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] The concept of managing infrastructure through code emerged from early configuration management practices.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] In the 1990s, tools such as CFEngine, created by Mark Burgess in 1993, introduced the idea of describing system configuration in a declarative language rather than executing manual commands, laying the intellectual groundwork for IaC.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] IaC emerged as organizations began managing larger and more complex infrastructure, particularly with the growth of cloud computing and the need to provision resources consistently and at scale.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Treating infrastructure configuration like software - storing it in version control, reviewing it, and deploying it automatically allowed teams to reduce manual errors and reproduce environments reliably.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] The ability to treat infrastructure as code and use the same tools as any other software project would allow developers to rapidly deploy applications.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] The value of IaC can be broken down into three measurable categories: cost, speed, and risk.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Cost reduction aims at helping not only the enterprise financially, but also in terms of people and effort, meaning that by removing the manual component, organizations are able to refocus their efforts on other enterprise tasks.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure automation enables speed through faster execution when configuring your infrastructure and provides visibility to help other teams across the enterprise work quickly and more efficiently.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Automation removes the risk associated with human error, like manual misconfiguration; removing this can decrease downtime and increase reliability.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] These outcomes and attributes help the enterprise move toward implementing a culture of DevOps: the combined work of development and operations.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] There are generally two approaches to IaC: declarative (functional) vs. imperative (procedural).
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] The difference between the declarative and the imperative approach is essentially *what* versus *how*.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach focuses on what the eventual target configuration should be; the imperative focuses on how the infrastructure is to be changed to meet this.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach defines the desired state and the system executes what needs to happen to achieve that desired state.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Imperative defines specific commands that need to be executed in the appropriate order to end with the desired conclusion.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure as Code (IaC) allows organizations to manage servers and their configurations using code.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] There are two ways to apply these configurations to servers: the 'push' and 'pull' methods.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'push' method, the system controlling the configuration directly sends instructions to the server.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'pull' method, the server retrieves its own instructions from the controlling system.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] There are many tools that fulfill infrastructure automation capabilities and use IaC.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Broadly speaking, any framework or tool that performs changes or configures infrastructure declaratively or imperatively based on a programmatic approach can be considered IaC.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Traditionally, server (lifecycle) automation and configuration management tools were used to accomplish IaC.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Now enterprises are also using continuous configuration automation tools or stand-alone IaC frameworks, such as Microsoft’s PowerShell DSC or AWS CloudFormation.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] All continuous configuration automation (CCA) tools can be thought of as extensions of traditional IaC frameworks.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] They leverage IaC to change, configure, and automate infrastructure, and they also provide visibility, efficiency, and flexibility in how infrastructure is managed.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] These additional attributes provide enterprise-level security and compliance.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Community content is a key determinant of an open-source CCA tool's quality.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] According to Gartner, the value of CCA tools is "as dependent on user-community-contributed content and support as it is on the commercial maturity and performance of the automation tooling".
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Established vendors such as Puppet and Chef have created their own communities.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Chef has Chef Community Repository and Puppet has PuppetForge.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Other vendors rely on adjacent communities and leverage other IaC frameworks such as PowerShell DSC.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] New vendors are emerging that are not content-driven, but model-driven with the intelligence in the product to deliver content.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] These visual, object-oriented systems work well for developers, but they are especially useful to production-oriented DevOps and operations constituents that value models versus scripting for content.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] As the field continues to develop and change, the community-based content will become ever more important to how IaC tools are used, unless they are model-driven and object-oriented.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Other tools include AWS CloudFormation, cdist, StackStorm, Juju, and Step CI.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] IaC can be a key attribute of enabling best practices in DevOps.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Developers become more involved in defining configuration and Ops teams get involved earlier in the development process.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Tools that utilize IaC bring visibility to the state and configuration of servers and ultimately provide the visibility to users within the enterprise, which brings teams together to maximize their efforts.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Automation in general aims to take the confusion and error-prone aspect of manual processes and make it more efficient, and productive.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Allowing for better software and applications to be created with flexibility, less downtime, and an overall cost-effective way for the company.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] IaC is intended to reduce the complexity that kills efficiency out of manual configuration.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] Automation and collaboration are considered central points in DevOps; infrastructure automation tools are often included as components of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:serverless-framework/infrastructure-as-code] The 2020 Cloud Threat Report released by Unit 42 (the threat intelligence unit of cybersecurity provider Palo Alto Networks) identified around 200,000 potential vulnerabilities in infrastructure-as-code templates.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:serverless-framework/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] A **software framework** is software that provides reusable, generic functionality which developers can extend or customize to create complete solutions.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] It offers an abstraction layer over lower-level code and infrastructure, allowing developers to focus on implementing business logic rather than building common functionality from scratch.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] Generally, a framework is intended to enhance productivity by allowing developers to focus on satisfying business requirements rather than reimplementing generic functionality.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] Frameworks often include support programs, compilers, software development kits, code libraries, toolsets, and APIs that integrate various components within a larger software platform or environment.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] Unlike a library, where user code controls the program's control flow, a framework implements inversion of control by dictating the overall structure and calling user code at predefined extension points (e.g., through template methods or hooks).
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] Frameworks also provide default behaviours that work out-of-the-box, structured mechanisms for extensibility, and a fixed core that accepts extensions (e.g., plugins or subclasses) without direct modification.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] A framework differs from an application that can be extended—such as a web browser via an extension or a video game via a mod—in that it is intentionally incomplete scaffolding designed to be completed through its extension points while following specific architectural patterns.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] For example, a team using a web framework to develop a banking website can focus on writing banking business logic rather than handling low-level details like web request processing or state management.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] According to Pree, software frameworks consist of *frozen spots* and *hot spots*.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] *Frozen spots* define the overall architecture of a software system, that is to say its basic components and the relationships between them.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] These remain unchanged (frozen) in any instantiation of the application framework.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] *Hot spots* represent the parts where the programmers using the framework add their own code to add the functionality specific to their own project.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] The necessary functionality can be implemented by using the Template Method Pattern in which the *frozen spots* are known as invariant methods and the *hot spots* are known as variant or hook methods.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] The invariant methods in the superclass provide default behaviour while the hook methods in each subclass provide custom behaviour.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] When developing a concrete software system with a software framework, developers utilize the hot spots according to the specific needs and requirements of the system.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] Software frameworks rely on the Hollywood Principle: "Don't call us, we'll call you." This means that the user-defined classes (for example, new subclasses) receive messages from the predefined framework classes.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] Developers usually handle this by implementing superclass abstract methods.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] One potential downside of using a framework is that it adds to the size of a program, a phenomenon termed code bloat.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] This can be exacerbated by using multiple, sometimes competing, frameworks in the same codebase.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] Learning how to use a framework can be substantial.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] The intended efficiencies of using the framework may be outweighed by the cost to learn it, especially for a framework that is new to the development staff.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] However, once a framework is learned, development team speed may increase for future work.
[src:serverless-framework/software-framework] Some claim that the most effective frameworks evolve from re-factoring an existing solution, such as a generic one-size-fits-all framework developed by third parties for general purposes, rather than from green-field development.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Custom data types are allowed, but YAML natively encodes scalars (such as strings, integers, and floats), lists, and associative arrays (also known as maps, dictionaries or hashmaps).
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] These data types are based on the Perl programming language, though all commonly used high-level programming languages share very similar concepts.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] The colon-centered syntax, used for expressing key-value pairs, is inspired by electronic mail headers as defined in RFC 822, and the document separator `---` is borrowed from MIME (RFC 2046).
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Escape sequences are reused from C, and whitespace wrapping for multi-line strings is inspired by HTML.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Lists and hashes can contain nested lists and hashes, forming a tree structure; arbitrary graphs can be represented using YAML aliases (similar to XML in SOAP).
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] YAML is intended to be read and written in streams, a feature inspired by SAX.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Support for reading and writing YAML is available for many programming languages.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Some source-code editors such as Vim, Emacs, and various integrated development environments have features that make editing YAML easier, such as folding up nested structures or automatically highlighting syntax errors.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] The official recommended filename extension for YAML files has been `.yaml` since 2006.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] In 2024, the MIME type `application/yaml` has been finalized.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] YAML (/ˈjæməl/, rhymes with *camel*) was first proposed by Clark Evans in 2001, who designed it together with Ingy döt Net and Oren Ben-Kiki.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Originally YAML was said to mean *Yet Another Markup Language*, because it was released in an era that saw a proliferation of markup languages for presentation and connectivity (HTML, XML, SGML, etc.).
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] A cheat sheet and full specification are available at the official site.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] The following is a synopsis of the basic elements.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] YAML accepts the entire Unicode character set, except for some control characters, and may be encoded in any one of UTF-8, UTF-16 or UTF-32.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Conventional block format uses a hyphen+space to begin a new item in list.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Optional inline format is delimited by comma+space and enclosed in brackets (similar to JSON).
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Keys are separated from values by a colon+space.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Indented blocks, common in YAML data files, use indentation and new lines to separate the key/value pairs.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Inline blocks, common in YAML data streams, use comma+space to separate the key/value pairs between braces.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] There are two ways to write multi-line strings, one preserving newlines (using the `|` character) and one that folds the newlines (using the `>` character), both followed by a newline character.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] By default, the leading indentation (of the first line) and trailing whitespace are stripped, though other behavior can be explicitly specified.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Folded text converts newlines to spaces and removes leading whitespace.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Objects and lists are important components in yaml and can be mixed.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] The first example is a list of key-value objects, all people from the Smith family.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] The second lists them by gender; it is a key-value object containing two lists.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Features that distinguish YAML from the capabilities of other data-serialization languages are structures, and data and composite keys.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] YAML structures enable storage of multiple documents within a single file, usage of references for repeated nodes, and usage of arbitrary nodes as keys.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] For clarity, compactness, and avoiding data entry errors, YAML provides node anchors (using `&`) and references (using `*`).
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] References to the anchor work for all data types (see the ship-to reference in the example below).
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Below is an example of a queue in an instrument sequencer in which two steps are referenced without being fully described.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Explicit data typing is seldom seen in the majority of YAML documents since YAML autodetects simple types.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Data types can be divided into three categories: core, defined, and user-defined.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Core are ones expected to exist in any parser (e.g. floats, ints, strings, lists, maps, ...).
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Many more advanced data types, such as binary data, are defined in the YAML specification but not supported in all implementations.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Finally YAML defines a way to extend the data type definitions locally to accommodate user-defined classes, structures or primitives (e.g. quad-precision floats).
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] YAML autodetects the datatype of the entity, but sometimes one wants to cast the datatype explicitly.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] The most common situation is where a single-word string that looks like a number, Boolean or tag requires disambiguation by surrounding it with quotes or using an explicit datatype tag.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Not every implementation of YAML has every specification-defined data type.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] These built-in types use a double-exclamation sigil prefix (`!!`).
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Particularly interesting ones not shown here are sets, ordered maps, timestamps, and hexadecimal.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Here is an example of base64-encoded binary data.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Many implementations of YAML can support user-defined data types for object serialization.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Local data types are not universal data types but are defined in the application using the YAML parser library.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Local data types use a single exclamation mark (`!`).
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] YAML supports composite keys, which consist of multiple values.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Such keys are useful for coordinate transformations, multi-field identifiers, test cases with compound conditions, and the like.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Data-structure hierarchy is maintained by outline indentation.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Notice that strings do not require enclosure in quotation marks.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] The specific number of spaces in the indentation is unimportant as long as parallel elements have the same left justification and the hierarchically nested elements are indented further.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] This sample document defines an associative array with 7 top level keys: one of the keys, "items", contains a 2-element list, each element of which is itself an associative array with differing keys.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Relational data and redundancy removal are displayed: the "ship-to" associative array content is copied from the "bill-to" associative array's content as indicated by the anchor (`&`) and reference (`*`) labels.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Optional blank lines can be added for readability.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Multiple documents can exist in a single file/stream and are separated by `---`.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] An optional `...` can be used at the end of a file (useful for signaling an end in streamed communications without closing the pipe).
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Because YAML primarily relies on outline indentation for structure, it is especially resistant to delimiter collision.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] YAML may be placed in JSON by quoting and escaping all interior quotation marks.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] YAML may be placed in XML by escaping reserved characters (`<`, `>`, `&`, `'`, `"`) and converting whitespace, or by placing it in a CDATA section.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Unlike JSON, which can only represent data in a hierarchical model with each child node having a single parent, YAML also offers a simple relational scheme that allows repeats of identical data to be referenced from two or more points in the tree rather than entered redundantly at those points.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] This is similar to the facility IDREF built into XML.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] The YAML parser then expands these references into the fully populated data structures they imply when read in, so whatever program is using the parser does not have to be aware of a relational encoding model, unlike XML processors, which do not expand references.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] This expansion can enhance readability while reducing data entry errors in configuration files or processing protocols where many parameters remain the same in a sequential series of records while only a few vary.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] An example being that "ship-to" and "bill-to" records in an invoice are nearly always the same data.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] YAML is purely a data-representation language and thus has no executable commands.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] While validation and safe parsing is inherently possible in any data language, implementation is such a notorious pitfall that YAML's lack of an associated command language may be a relative security benefit.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] However, YAML allows language-specific tags so that arbitrary local objects can be created by a parser that supports those tags.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Any YAML parser that allows sophisticated object instantiation to be executed opens the potential for an injection attack.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Perl parsers that allow loading of objects of arbitrary classes create so-called "blessed" values.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Using these values may trigger unexpected behavior, e.g. if the class uses overloaded operators.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] This may lead to execution of arbitrary Perl code.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] The situation is similar for Python or Ruby parsers.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] The YAML specification identifies an *instance document* as a "Presentation" or "character stream".
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] The primary logical structures in a YAML instance document are scalars, sequences, and mappings.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] The YAML specification also indicates some basic constraints that apply to these primary logical structures.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] For example, according to the specification, mapping keys do not have an order.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] In every case where node order is significant, a sequence must be used.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Moreover, in defining conformance for YAML processors, the YAML specification defines two primary operations: *dump* and *load*.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] All YAML-compliant processors must provide *at least* one of these operations, and may optionally provide both.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Finally, the YAML specification defines an *information model* or "representation graph", which must be created during processing for both *dump* and *load* operations, although this representation need not be made available to the user through an API.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] JSON syntax is a basis of YAML version 1.2, which was promulgated with the express purpose of bringing YAML "into compliance with JSON as an official subset".
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Though prior versions of YAML were not strictly compatible, the discrepancies were rarely noticeable, and most JSON documents can be parsed by some YAML parsers such as Syck.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] This is because JSON's semantic structure is equivalent to the optional "inline-style" of writing YAML.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] While extended hierarchies can be written in inline-style like JSON, this is not a recommended YAML style except when it aids clarity.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] YAML has many additional features not present in JSON, including comments, extensible data types, relational anchors, strings without quotation marks, and mapping types preserving key order.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Due to the conciseness, JSON serialization and deserialization is much faster than YAML.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] TOML was designed to be an advancement of the .ini file format.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] YAML makes minimal use of indicator characters compared to TOML's strict requirement of quotation marks and square brackets.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] YAML's use of significant indentation has been contrasted with the dot notation of TOML's key and table names to convey the same semantic structure.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Opinions differ on which convention leads to more-readable configuration files.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] YAML lacks the notion of tag attributes that are found in XML.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Instead YAML has extensible type declarations (including class types for objects).
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] YAML itself does not have XML's language-defined document schema descriptors that allow, for example, a document to self-validate.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] However, there are several externally defined schema descriptor languages for YAML (e.g.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Doctrine, Kwalify and Rx) that fulfill that role.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Moreover, the semantics provided by YAML's language-defined type declarations in the YAML document itself frequently relaxes the need for a validator in simple, common situations.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Additionally, YAXML, which represents YAML data structures in XML, allows XML schema importers and output mechanisms like XSLT to be applied to YAML.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Comparison of data-serialization formats provides a more comprehensive comparison of YAML with other serialization formats.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] For fixed data structures, YAML files can simply be generated using *print* commands that write both the data and the YAML specific decoration.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] To dump varying, or complex, hierarchical data, however, a dedicated YAML *emitter* is preferable.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Similarly, simple YAML files (e.g. key-value pairs) are readily parsed with regular expressions.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] For more complex, or varying, data structures, a formal YAML *parser* is recommended.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] YAML emitters and parsers exist for many popular languages.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Most of them are written in the native language itself.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Some are language bindings of the C library *libyaml*; they may run faster.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] There used to be another C library, called *Syck*, written and orphaned by why the lucky stiff: it is unmaintained, there is no authoritative source bundle, and the web site has been hijacked.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Hence the only recommendable C library is *libyaml*.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] It was originally developed by Kirill Simonov.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] In 2018, development was resumed by the new maintainers Ian Cordasco and Ingy döt Net.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] C++ programmers have the choice between the C library *libyaml* and the C++ library *libyaml-cpp*.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Both have completely independent code bases and completely different APIs.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] The library *libyaml-cpp* still has a major version number of 0, indicating that the API may change at any moment, as happened indeed after version 0.3.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] There is a grammar-focused implementation written in C#, with an aim on extensions for the nested elements.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Some implementations of YAML, such as Perl's YAML.pm, will load an entire file (stream) and parse it *en masse*.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Other implementations like PyYaml are lazy and iterate over the next document only upon request.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] For very large files in which one plans to handle the documents independently, instantiating the entire file before processing may be prohibitive.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] Thus in YAML.pm, occasionally one must chunk a file into documents and parse those individually.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] YAML makes this easy, since this simply requires splitting on the document end marker, which is defined as three periods at the start of a line followed by a whitespace (and possible a comment).
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] In static, compiled languages, this instantiation is complex to achieve and is quite often not implemented.
[src:serverless-framework/yaml] The perceived flaws and complexity of YAML has led to the emergence of stricter alternatives such as StrictYAML and NestedText.
